The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Extracting my stated preferences and dislikes: I favor concise, front‑of‑mix records with charismatic, forward lead vocals; minimal reverb/overdubs; preserved micro‑dynamics and warm mastering that keeps midrange punch and avoids brick‑wall loudness. I prize intimate, vocal‑forward mixes with close, warm lead takes and clear instrument separation when arrangements are economical and serve immediacy. I specifically dislike piano‑anchored, 1970s‑style presentations that center instruments (and stacked vocals) at the expense of a single, immediate lead, murky or over‑busy production, excessive ornamentation, and heavy brick‑wall mastering.
Evaluation and choice: The Dinah Washington anthology best matches those preferences. Its close‑mic, vocal‑forward takes with preserved microdynamics, minimal compression and warm analog‑tape grit align directly with my desire for an immediate, tactile lead vocal and mastering that preserves dynamics and midrange presence. The tight remastering that retains delicate cymbal shimmer and tactile upright‑bass supports clear instrument separation without cluttering or competing with the vocal — exactly the economical arrangements and intimacy I value. The anthology’s curated sequencing and emphasis on raw vocal presence favor focused, detail‑oriented listening rather than sprawling, instrument‑centered arrangements.
Tapestry, while excellent in many respects (close‑miked vocals, low reverb, concise 3–4 minute songs, restrained percussion and warm analogue mastering preserving headroom), is explicitly a piano‑first, piano‑anchored, 1970s singer‑songwriter presentation. That piano‑front approach conflicts with my stated dislike of piano‑anchored 1970s presentations that tend to center instruments and reduce the impact of a single, immediate lead vocal. Even though Tapestry’s mastering and song lengths are attractive to me, the centrality of grand piano as the dominant instrument makes it less aligned with my priority for a forward, singular lead vocal and economical arrangements where piano supports rather than leads.
Therefore I select the Dinah Washington anthology as the CD that most closely matches my preference for intimate, vocal‑forward, minimally compressed, warm‑mastered recordings with clear separation and restrained arrangements, and I reject Tapestry because its piano‑centric 1970s aesthetic works against my stated dislike of instrument‑centered mixes that can diminish a single immediate lead.

