- Arrangement density and timbre: synth/beat‑forward pop production is inherently more ornamented and rhythmically propulsive than the restrained, intimate singer‑songwriter records I prefer.
Decision and rationale
I choose the Intimate Simon & Garfunkel best‑of because its acoustic, minimally overdubbed recordings with warm, low‑compression analogue tone, delicate fingerpicking and clear lead separation align more closely with my core priorities: preserved headroom and microdynamics, intimate front‑of‑mix vocals, restrained arrangements, and minimal production clutter. Those attributes directly address my dislikes (murkiness, overbusy production, heavy compression and buried leads) and deliver the immediacy and tonal warmth I prize.
I reject the Eurythmics remaster not because it is objectively bad—its punchy, hook‑driven, front‑of‑mix pop production will serve listeners who want immediate, bass‑forward grooves—but because its synth‑bass emphasis, propulsive percussion and more aggressive compression run counter to my preference for acoustic restraint, analogue openness, preserved microdynamics and minimal ornamentation. In short, Simon & Garfunkel better preserves the intimacy, space, and dynamics I value; Eurythmics prioritizes rhythmic punch and low‑end drive that I’m predisposed to avoid.

